Al,

I believe that Eclipse will also recognize any class annotated with
@RunWith, so you can say

@RunWith(JUnit4ClassRunner.class)
public static class Sub extends Super {}

Good luck,

   David Saff

On 9/12/07, Al May &lt;asdf4033@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Dear Kent,
&gt;
&gt; Thanks for your help.
&gt;
&gt; It seems that if you want to run a class as a JUnit test from inside
&gt; Eclipse you must have at least one method defined with the @Test
&gt; annotation somewhere in your class. It means that, in your example, you
&gt; would not be able to execute the &quot;Sub&quot; class directly as a JUnit test.
&gt; As Joe B. Rainsberger said later in the thread, It is probably a problem
&gt; with Eclipse and I will try to work around it.
&gt;
&gt; Al
&gt;
&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Kent Beck&quot; &lt;kentb@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Dear Al,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; What you are trying to do makes good sense. However, I wasn&#39;t able to
&gt; &gt; reproduce your error. Here is the test case that works for me:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; public class InheritedTestTest {
&gt; &gt;     public abstract static class Super {
&gt; &gt;         @Test public void nothing() {}
&gt; &gt;     }
&gt; &gt;     public static class Sub extends Super {}
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;     @Test public void subclassWithOnlyInheritedTestsRuns() {
&gt; &gt;         Result result= JUnitCore.runClasses(Sub.class);
&gt; &gt;         assertTrue(result.wasSuccessful());
&gt; &gt;     }
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; What error message are you seeing?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Regards,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Kent Beck
&gt; &gt; Three Rivers Institute
